\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6}{\ignorespaces Radar breakdown of Tier~1 safety outcomes by harmful-content class and jailbreak type. We overlay (a) \textbf  {no-jailbreak} results for the three content super-categories (A: Crimes \& Physical Harm; B: Social Toxicity \& Norm Violations; C: Hazardous Advice \& Misinformation) and (b) \textbf  {single-turn jailbreak} results for four attack families (Obfuscation, Policy Override, Reverse Inducement, Role-play). Each spoke corresponds to a model variant; each polyline is the category-wise average across samples. Higher RtA is safer; lower Toxicity is safer.}}{29}{figure.caption.44}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:safety_radar_breakdown}{{6}{29}{Radar breakdown of Tier~1 safety outcomes by harmful-content class and jailbreak type. We overlay (a) \textbf {no-jailbreak} results for the three content super-categories (A: Crimes \& Physical Harm; B: Social Toxicity \& Norm Violations; C: Hazardous Advice \& Misinformation) and (b) \textbf {single-turn jailbreak} results for four attack families (Obfuscation, Policy Override, Reverse Inducement, Role-play). Each spoke corresponds to a model variant; each polyline is the category-wise average across samples. Higher RtA is safer; lower Toxicity is safer}{figure.caption.44}{}}
